fr:mainmatter.fr:p:
We assume that there're enough universe, i.e.,
    for every finite list of types in context 
             \Gamma _1\vdash  A_1\space \space \text {type},\cdots ,\Gamma _n\vdash  A_n\space \space \text {type}     
    there is a universe \mathcal {U} that contains each A_i in the sense that \mathcal {U} comes equipped with
             \Gamma _i\vdash \check {A_i}:\mathcal {U}     
    for which the following judgement holds:
             \Gamma _i \vdash \mathcal {T}(\check {A_i})\equiv  A_i\space \space \text {type}

The successor universee \mathcal {U}^+ of a universe \mathcal {U} is defined using universe postulate
    with the following contexts:
             \vdash \mathcal {U}\space \space \text {type}\quad  X:\mathcal {U}\vdash \mathcal {T}(X)\space \space \text {type}     
    It therefore contains the type \mathcal {U} as well as type in \mathcal {U}, in the following sense
             \begin {align*}             &\vdash \check {\mathcal {U}}:\mathcal {U}^+\\              &\vdash \mathcal {T}^+(\check {\mathcal {U}})\equiv \mathcal {U}\space \text {type}\\             &X:\mathcal {U}\vdash \check {\mathcal {T}}(X):\mathcal {U}^+\\              &X:\mathcal {U}\vdash \mathcal {T}^+(\check {\mathcal {T}}(X))\equiv \mathcal {T}(X)\space \text {type}          \end {align*}

Let C and D be categories and F,G:C\to  D be functors.
    A natural transformation \alpha :F\Rightarrow   G is 
    an assignment to every object x\in  C of a morphism \alpha _x:F(x)\to  G(x) in D,
    (called the component of \alpha  at x)
    the following diagram commutes in D:


      \usepackage {tikz-cd}
      \usepackage {amssymb}


        \begin {tikzcd}
            {F(x)} && {F(y)} \\
            \\
            {G(x)} && {G(y)}
            \arrow ["{F(f)}", from=1-1, to=1-3]
            \arrow ["{G(f)}", from=3-1, to=3-3]
            \arrow ["{\alpha _x}", from=1-1, to=3-1]
            \arrow ["{\alpha _y}", from=1-3, to=3-3]
        \end {tikzcd}

Given any category \mathcal {C}, and any set \{X_i\}_{i\in I} of its objects, the product of all these objects is, if it exists, an object \prod _{i\in I} X_i \in \mathcal {C} equipped with morphisms (projections) p_i : \left (\prod _{i\in I} X_i\right ) \to X_i for each i\in I, such that it is universal with this property, i.e. such that given any other object Q\in C with morphisms Q \xrightarrow {f_i} X_i there is a unique morphism (f_i)_{i\in I} : Q \to \prod _{i\in I} X_i where the following diagram commutes:
\usepackage {tikz-cd} \usepackage {amssymb}
\begin {tikzcd} Q \\ \\ {\prod _{i\in I} X_i} && {X_i} \arrow ["{p_i}", from=3-1, to=3-3] \arrow ["{f_i}", from=1-1, to=3-3] \arrow ["{(f_i)_{i\in I}}"', from=1-1, to=3-1] \end {tikzcd}

A terminal object in a category \mathcal {C} is an object \top  of \mathcal {C} 
    satisfying the following universal property: for any object X in \mathcal {C},
    there exists a unique morphism !:X\to  \top .

For \mathcal {C} a category and X, Y \in \text {Ob}{\mathcal {C}}, the coproduct is an object X\sqcup Y equipped with two morphisms i_X:X\to X\sqcup Y and i_Y:Y\to X\sqcup Y such that it is universal with this property. That is, for any object Z and morphisms f:X\to Z and g:Y\to Z, there exists a unique morphism \langle f, g\rangle :X\sqcup Y\to Z such that the following diagram commutes:
\usepackage {tikz-cd} \usepackage {amssymb}
\begin {tikzcd} X && {X\sqcup Y} && Y \\ \\ && Z \arrow ["{[f,g]}"', dashed, from=1-3, to=3-3] \arrow ["f"', from=1-1, to=3-3] \arrow ["{i_Y}"', from=1-5, to=1-3] \arrow ["{i_X}", from=1-1, to=1-3] \arrow ["g", from=1-5, to=3-3] \end {tikzcd}

A monad of a category \mathcal {C} is an endofunctor M:\mathcal {C}\to \mathcal {C} with two natural transformations \eta :\text {id}_{\mathcal {C}}\Rightarrow M and \mu :M^2\Rightarrow M satisfying the following conditions:
\usepackage {tikz-cd} \usepackage {amssymb}
\begin {tikzcd} {M^2(X)} && {M(X)} && {M^2(X)} \\ && {M(X)} \\ \\ & {M^3(X)} && {M^2(X)} \\ & {M^2(X)} && {M(X)} \arrow ["{\mu _{M(X)}}"', from=4-2, to=5-2] \arrow ["{\mu _X}", from=5-2, to=5-4] \arrow ["{1_{M(X)}}", from=1-3, to=2-3] \arrow ["{\mu _X}"', from=1-1, to=2-3] \arrow ["{M(\eta _X)}"', from=1-3, to=1-1] \arrow ["{\eta _{ M(X)}}", from=1-3, to=1-5] \arrow ["{\mu _X}", from=1-5, to=2-3] \arrow ["{\mu _X}", from=4-4, to=5-4] \arrow ["{M(\mu _X)}", from=4-2, to=4-4] \end {tikzcd}

Let C and D be categories and F,G:C\to  D be functors.
    A natural transformation \alpha :F\Rightarrow   G is 
    an assignment to every object x\in  C of a morphism \alpha _x:F(x)\to  G(x) in D,
    (called the component of \alpha  at x)
    the following diagram commutes in D:


      \usepackage {tikz-cd}
      \usepackage {amssymb}


        \begin {tikzcd}
            {F(x)} && {F(y)} \\
            \\
            {G(x)} && {G(y)}
            \arrow ["{F(f)}", from=1-1, to=1-3]
            \arrow ["{G(f)}", from=3-1, to=3-3]
            \arrow ["{\alpha _x}", from=1-1, to=3-1]
            \arrow ["{\alpha _y}", from=1-3, to=3-3]
        \end {tikzcd}
